We turn to a discussion of the changes of the device performance under device operation from a microscopic viewpoint. As presented in Fig. 2c, the JSC of the cell rapidly decreased (see the inset) and then gradually increased (see the main panel) when the Nspin increased under short-circuit conditions. The studies of organic solar cells have reported the JSC decrease due to charge-carrier scatterings by charge accumulation in cells22,33,34. When the charge-carrier scatterings occur due to hole accumulation or formation, the current density j of a solar cell may be described with a following equation based on the Matthiessen’s rule with charge density (n), electric elemental quantity (e), charge mobility (μ) in the cell, internal electric field (E), charge mobility before (μSC), and after hole accumulation (μHA), and a proportional constant (c)33,34:1j=neμE=neμSCμHAμHA+(μSC/c)NspinE.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
